{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bullock_ver01/data/sn82016181/00516999627/1938011001/0241.xml":{"full_text":"Local Business Tax\nBiggest Cloud on\n1938 s Horizon\nThe new year has rung up the curtain on a Washing\nton business outlook as fair as Little Eva and with the\nmunicipal tax tangle the only real villain in the piece.\nHeads of the merchants\u2019. bankers\nand brokers associations seem to be\nagreed that with its peculiarly stable\nemployment level unaffected by the\nnation-wide recession, the Capital has\nnothing to fear within the next 12\nmonths except buyer loss of confi\ndence and governmental burdens.\nNOT A BAD YEAR\nNineteen Thirty-Seven compared\nwell, overall, with the banner year of\n1936, these leaders admit, and there is\nno reason to expect any less this\nyear. Local business is looking for\nward to abandonment of the munici\npal business privilege tax and modifi\ncation at least, of the Federal Gov\nernment's capital gains and losses and\nLegislation al\nexcess profits levies\nready blueprinted should solve that\npart of its problem.\nThe loss of buyer confidence is a\npsychological factor that should cor\nrect itself\nLocally. it was born to\na large extent of the market\u2019s steady\ndeflation of paper profits and of\nnatural reaction to hard-luck stories\nfrom industrial centers which have\nfelt the recession.\nThe real estate market here has\nsuffered from this timidity, in the\nopinion of President Morton J. Lucns\nof the Washington Real Estate Board\nBut Luchs believes that spring will\nsee a revival of home purchasing\nthat will move available dwellings\nand encourage further new residence\nconstruction.\nVACANCY AVERAGE LOW\nLuchs also points out that while\nnew apartment construction is sub\nsiding and that as a result most\nof the existing vacancies should be\nabsorbed, that the present vacancy\naverage is only 5 or 6 per cent com\npared with the 10 per cent considered\nnormal not long ago. He added that\ninvestment property sales have picked\nup remarkably since November\nThe high standing of new home\npurchasers here is indicated by rec\nords of the District Federal Housing\nAdministration office. Director Henry\nDearing points out that of the 2397\nloans insured in this area, no prop\nerty has been conveyed to the Fed\neral Housing Administrator in ex\nchange for debentures. Eight of the\nloans have been for large-scale rental\nprojects which will accommodate a\ntotal of more than 2400 families\nThe constancy of purchasing power\nin Washington was emphasized by\nPresident Ford E Young of the Mer\nchants Manufacturers Association\nin pointing out that for the first 11\nmonths of 1937 retail trade here\nshowed an actual gain of one-tenth\nof 1 per cent over the 1936 record\nBank clearings in the same period\ntopped the 1936 figure by more than\n$130,000,000, or 8 per cent, and pos\ntal receipts rose about 1 per cent\nNEW CAR SALES OFF\nThere was a 10 per cent decline in\nnew car sales from the 1936 all-time\nhigh, Young admitted, but the 11\nmonth total of 26,944 passenger car\nsales still exceeded the comparable\nfigure for 1935, the former banner\nyear. Oil burner sales were off about\n11 per cent from the 1936 record, but\nWashington anthracite and bitumi\nnous coal tonnage registered a slight\nincrease for the first eight months\nof the fiscal year, beginning April 1.\nThe far-flung publicity and adver\ntising activities of the Greater Na\ntional Capital Committee of the\nBoard of Trade bore fruit in scores of\nconventions and hundreds of thou\nsands of tourists estimated to have\nspent $50,000,000 in Washington\u2014an\neconomic factor second only to the\nFederal pay roll here.\nRobert J. Cottrell, executive sec\nretary of the Board of Trade, pre\ndicts that 1938 will bring some order\nout of the chaos of municipal busi\nness taxation He expects much from\nthe hearings to be opened shortly\nby the fiscal affairs sub-committee\nof the House District Committee.\nA rV-eA is ASEMED\n\"It is earnestly hoped, he said to\nday, \"that thru them some well de\nveloped policy of future municipal\noperation and financing which will\ncontribute to the taxpayers\u2019 com\nfort, will emerge\nPresident William Montgomery of\nthe Acacia Mutual Life Insurance Co.,\nwhich has its home offices here, be\nlieves that \u201call the elements essen\ntial to national prosperity\u201d are pres\nent and that only \u2018\u2018confidence in our\nselves, confidence in the permanence\nand security of those institutions\nwhich constitute our most priceless\nheritage\u2019 is needed to produce a per\nmanent upswing.\nF. D. Schedules Talks\nWith Utility Executives\nEditorial, \u201cF. D. Learns From\nT. R.,\" on Page 16.\nBy United Press\nPresident Roosevelt will resume\nconferences with utility experts to\nmorrow, the White House announced\ntoday, as the Utilities Consumers Na\ntional Policy Committee recommended\na- thoro revision of rate making bases\nand state and Federal regulatory\nstatutes.\nSuch revision, the consumers' com\nmittee said, is a necessary prelude\nto true co-operation between private\npower companies and the public.\nPresident Roosevelt\u2019s additional dis\ncussions, the White House said, will\nrepresent continuation of previous\nconferences in which he has sought\nto harmonize differences of the Ad\nministration with the power opera\nHe hopes to release a huge\ntors.\npool of private funds for extension of\nin\nutilities construction\nagainst business recession.\na\ndrive\nSeeks Ban on Firms\nHolding Bank Stocks\nBy United Press\nRep. Wright Patman\nI\n(D., Tex\nprepared today to introduce in Con\ngress a bill which would impose a\n\"death sentence\" on bank holding\ncompanies.\nThe measure, which has the sup\nport of some Administration fiscal ot- i\nficials, would prohibit any corporation\nfrom directly holding in its own right,\nstock in any bank insured by the\ntion.\nFederal Deposit Insurance Corpora-\nIn specifying insured banks.\nPatman aimed not only at holding\ncompanies operating in the national\nbank field, but at state banks.\nThere is now in the Senate a bill\nintroduced by Sen William Gibbs\nMcAdoo (D. Calif), which would\ni force corporations to divest themselves\ni of all but 10 per cent ot their stocK\ni holdings in national banks.\nHousing Shortage\nHeld Real Menace\nBy J. R. RIDGWAY\nChairman, Investors Syndicate\ni NEW YORK, Jan. 10\u2014Intensive re\nsearch in home building trends thru\nout the United States, and critical\ni analysis of housing activities since the\nbeginning of 1929 reveal a constantly\ni growing shortage which may well\nprove dangerous if continued.\nWhile varying in degree. this short\nage is encountered in every section\nof the country. New housing is defi\nnitely falling far behind requirements.\nTwo-Story Transformer\nA million-volt transformer installed\ny Westinghouse at the Los Angeles\nInstitute of Radiology as part of the\nII\nnewest weapon against cancer, con\nsists of five 200,000-volt units stacked\nto a height ot two stories\nit sup\nplies current to the world's largest\nX-ray machine for practical treat\nment ot cancer\nARE THEY SAFE?\n3\n4.\n9\nSdP\u201d\nFROM FIRE OR THE\nMIDNIGHT PRO WLER!\nY(\nARE\nSAFE\nINCUR\nVAULTS,\n\u2022y\nInsurance Policies\nDeeds\nMortgage Paper*\nStock Certificate*\nBond*\nJewelry\nPut them in a safe place such as a\nprivate box in the Safe Deposit\nVaults at the Munsey Trust Co.\n\n$3 a Year and Up\nTHE MUNSEY TRUST CO.\nPenna. Ave. Bet. 13th and 14th Sts. N. W.\nMunsey Building\nMember: Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.\nf\n1\nComplete\nBANKING SERVICE\nAvailable to Eight Distinct Washington Business Communities\nMAIN OFFICE\n1503 Pennsylvania Avenne\n(Opposite U. S. Treasury)\n19)\nw\n3\na\u2019y\nWe\nL\u2019aamng\n12%\nri\nft\nv V\nwwreoo\nt\n53\n3\nmiin J 2\nNORTHWEST\n18th St. and Columbia Rd.\nst\n11\nI\nSEVENTH STREET\n7th and Eye Sts. N. W.\nh.\n|4\n2* **7,\n*,0\nO the advantage\nof size and vol\nume of business trans\nactions the Riggs Na\ntional Bank adds the\nconvenience of offices\nlocated at eight stra\ntegic points. Here are\nfound complete facili\nties in every phase of\nbanking activity with\nexperienced officers\nand employees at\nyour command.\nPa.\nPim,\nMany Washington\nbusiness firms and in\ndividuals find it a dis\ntinct advantage to\nmaintain relations\nwith a Riggs National\nunit.\nCh\nT\ntil\n\u2014T***\nNyingmywoi\nt\n\nFARMERS MECHANICS\nWise. Ave. and M bl. N. W.\nPARK ROAD\n19th and Park Rd N W.\nAwa\nI\nDUPONT\n1913 Mass. Ave. N W.\n\u25a0La\nis\ns\ns\nst\nI t\n\nHASE\nconn\nenUaMortho\"\nAvC\nEight\nConvenient\nLocutions\nThe\nf\n\n\nthen\nr\nRiggs National Bank\nMain Office. 1503 Pennsylvania Ave. N. W.\nOppesite U. S. Treasury\nEOBERT V. FLEMING. President\nMember, federal Depaeit Iruurance Corporation\nA\u2019zros,\nWar,\n\nLi","height":"21288","width":"14504"}}
